<p><sup><a name="fn77" href="#fnB77">[75]</a></sup> 	Beyond assuming that
animals are sentient (see above n 8), it is beyond the scope of this article to
explore arguments about the
moral status of animals. The focus on
inconsistencies in regulatory approaches to the treatment of different
categories of animal
is not intended to divert attention from the importance of
addressing first order questions about the moral status of animals. For
extended
accounts of the moral incoherency in our treatment of animals, both as between
human and non-human animals and as between
different species of non-human
animals see Peter Singer, <i>Practical Ethics</i> (2<sup>nd</sup> ed, 1993) and
Tom Regan, <i>The Case for Animal Rights</i> (1983).</p>
